Slide 3:
In a monolithic architecture, the entire application is built as one single unit.
All components such as the user interface, backend logic, database access, and authentication are tightly connected within the same application.
Because everything is connected:
•	A small change may require rebuilding and redeploying the entire system 
•	Scaling must be done for the whole application, even if only one part needs more resources 
•	If one component fails, it can affect the entire application 
But Modern applications rarely run in a single container.They usually contain multiple services, not just one container.
For example a typical web application includes:
•	A frontend application interacts with user
•	A backend that processes application logic
•	an API service that connects different services
•	A database that store application data.
•	A cache service stores temporary data
All these services need to communicate with each other.
For example, the frontend sends requests to the backend, and the backend reads or stores data in the database.
Sometimes a cache service is also used to store temporary data to improve performance.
Slide 4:
When running these services using containers, several challenges appear.
Services must start in the correct order, containers must communicate through networks, and developers must configure environment variables and settings for each service.
Managing all of this manually can quickly become complicated and error-prone.”
•	The commands can become long and complex
•	Containers must be connected manually through networks. So developers must manually configure networks so containers can communicate.
•	The startup order must be handled manually.For example the database must start before the application.
•	Environment variables and configuration settings must be set for each container
•	Sharing the setup with team members becomes difficult
Slide5 and 6:
“Docker Compose is a tool used to run multiple containers together as one application.
Instead of starting each container manually, we define everything in a single file called docker-compose.yml.
This file describes:
•	What services we need 
•	How they should run 
•	How they connect with each other 
Each service represents a part of the application, such as the frontend, backend, or database.
Docker Compose also handles:
•	Creating networks for communication 
•	Managing volumes for data storage 
•	Starting services in the correct order 
With one command, like docker compose up, the entire application is built and started.
This makes development easier, faster, and more organized.”

Slide 7:
In the services section, we define the configuration for each container or service in the application.
Each service includes settings such as:
Image – which container image to use 
Ports – how the service is exposed outside 
Volumes – where data is stored persistently 
Environment variables – used for configuration, like database credentials 
Networks – how services communicate with each other 
Dependencies – which service should start first 
These configurations control how each container runs and interacts with others.

Slide 12:
“To understand Docker Compose better, we can look at a sample voting application.
This example includes several services:
•	Voting web application
•	Result display application
•	Worker service
•	Redis queue
•	PostgreSQL database
Users vote using the vote application.
The vote is sent to Redis, which acts as a queue.
The worker service processes the vote and stores it in the PostgreSQL database.
The result application reads data from the database and displays the results.
Docker Compose connects all these services automatically.”

Vote Service
“The vote service represents the front-end application where users can vote.
This service is built from a local directory called vote using the Docker build process.
The target: dev option indicates that the development stage of the Dockerfile is used.
The service depends on Redis, which means Redis must be running and healthy before this service starts.
A healthcheck is defined to ensure the application is working properly.
Docker will periodically send a request to http://localhost to check if the service is responding.
The volumes section mounts the local vote folder into the container, allowing developers to modify code locally while the container runs.
The ports section maps port 8080 on the host machine to port 80 inside the container, allowing users to access the application through a browser.
Finally, the service is connected to two networks:
•	This service connects to both the front-tier and back-tier networks, because it communicates with users and backend services.”
________________________________________
2. Result Service
“The result service displays the voting results.
This service is also built from a local directory called result.
Instead of running a normal Node.js process, it uses nodemon through the entrypoint command.
Nodemon automatically restarts the application whenever code changes are detected, which is useful during development.
This service depends on the PostgreSQL database, ensuring the database is healthy before starting.
The volumes section mounts the result application code into the container.
Two ports are exposed:
•	8081:80 allows users to view the result web interface
•	9229:9229 is used for debugging Node.js applications.
Like the vote service, This service connects to both front-tier and back-tier networks.”
________________________________________
3. Worker Service
“The worker service processes votes in the background.
It is built from the worker directory.
This service depends on both Redis and the PostgreSQL database, meaning both services must be healthy before the worker starts.
The worker is connected only to the back-tier network because it communicates only with backend services, not with the user interface.”
________________________________________
4. Redis Service
“The Redis service acts as a temporary message queue for storing votes.
It uses the official Redis image called redis:alpine, which is a lightweight version of Redis.
A volume mounts a folder called healthchecks, which contains scripts used to verify whether Redis is working correctly.
A healthcheck command runs every 5 seconds to ensure Redis is functioning properly.
This service is connected to the back-tier network.”
________________________________________
5. Database Service (PostgreSQL)
“The db service runs a PostgreSQL database that stores the final vote results.
It uses the official Docker image postgres:15-alpine.
The environment variables define the database username and password.
A volume named db-data stores the database files.
This ensures that data is not lost even if the container stops or restarts.
Another volume mounts the healthcheck scripts.
A healthcheck script runs every 5 seconds to ensure the database is operational.
This service also belongs to the back-tier network.”
7. Volumes
“The file defines a volume called db-data.
Volumes are used to store persistent data.
In this case, it stores PostgreSQL database files so that data remains available even if the container restarts.”
________________________________________
8. Networks
“Two networks are defined in this file:
Front-tier network
This network is used for communication between user-facing services like the vote and result applications.
Back-tier network
This network is used for internal communication between backend services like Redis, worker, and the database.
Using multiple networks improves security and organization.”
